Operation: Offensive Defense (Signalforge Security Loop)

Core Idea

Don’t hunt real keys.
Simulate how they’d be lost—and prove you can’t be burned by it.

⸻

Phase 1 — Red Team Mindset (inside your own walls)

Think like failure, not like a hacker.

Ask:
	•	If I were sloppy, where would I leak a key?
	•	If I were tired, what would I accidentally commit?
	•	If I rushed deployment, what would I expose?

⸻

Most likely breakpoints (ranked reality, not theory)

1. Git leak
	•	.env accidentally committed
	•	config pushed to repo

2. Frontend exposure
	•	key in client-side code

3. Logging spill
	•	debug prints show secrets

4. Copy/paste drift
	•	keys in notes, docs, screenshots

⸻

Phase 2 — Simulated Breach Drill

Run this like a real exercise:

Scenario:

“A key was just exposed.”

Now answer:
	1.	How fast can I revoke it?
	2.	What systems break immediately?
	3.	Do I have backup keys ready?
	4.	What’s the cost impact if abused for 1 hour?

⸻

Phase 3 — Build Blast Radius Containment

This is where offense becomes architecture.

Limit damage BEFORE anything happens
	•	Separate keys per service
	•	Separate dev vs prod
	•	Add spending caps
	•	Add rate limits

⸻

Golden rule

No single key should be able to hurt you badly

⸻

Phase 4 — Tripwires (early detection)

Set alerts for:
	•	unusual usage spikes
	•	new IP patterns
	•	sudden cost jumps

⸻

Phase 5 — Automatic Response Loop

If triggered:
	1.	Rotate key
	2.	Swap environment variable
	3.	Restart service
	4.	Log incident
	5.	Patch root cause

⸻

Pantheon mapping (clean)
	•	Indigo Hammer → simulate failure
	•	Hogge Sieve → remove weak exposure paths
	•	Kintsugi → reinforce after break
	•	Checksum → verify integrity
	•	ZPC → turn risk → resilience

